sets

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict sets with age, gender, marital, education, family_income, number_volunteer_r and time_point (formula: sets ~ 1 + age + gender + marital + education + family_income + number_volunteer_r + time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.30) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.27. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, gender = female, marital = divorced, education = secondary, family_income = 0_10000, number_volunteer_r = 0 and time_point = 1st , is at 21.47 (S.E. = 3.01, p < .001, 95% CI [15.57, 27.37]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.02, S.E. = 0.03, p = 0.527, 95% CI [-0.08, 0.04]; Std. beta = -0.15, 95% CI [-0.62, 0.32])
  • The effect of gender [male] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.91, S.E. = 1.04, p = 0.382, 95% CI [-1.12, 2.94]; Std. beta = 0.45, 95% CI [-0.56, 1.47])
  • The effect of marital [married] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -3.05, S.E. = 1.74, p = 0.080, 95% CI [-6.46, 0.36]; Std. beta = -1.53, 95% CI [-3.24, 0.18])
  • The effect of marital [single] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -2.74, S.E. = 1.72, p = 0.111, 95% CI [-6.11, 0.63]; Std. beta = -1.37, 95% CI [-3.06, 0.31])
  • The effect of education [post-secondary] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.77, S.E. = 1.29, p = 0.549, 95% CI [-1.76, 3.31]; Std. beta = 0.39, 95% CI [-0.88, 1.66])
  • The effect of education [university] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.67, S.E. = 0.90, p = 0.456, 95% CI [-1.09, 2.43]; Std. beta = 0.34, 95% CI [-0.55, 1.22])
  • The effect of family income [10001_20000] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.87, S.E. = 1.24, p = 0.480, 95% CI [-1.55, 3.30]; Std. beta = 0.44, 95% CI [-0.78, 1.65])
  • The effect of family income [20001_30000] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.01, S.E. = 1.29, p = 0.991, 95% CI [-2.51, 2.54]; Std. beta = 7.48e-03, 95% CI [-1.26, 1.27])
  • The effect of family income [30001_40000] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 1.37, S.E. = 1.20, p = 0.253, 95% CI [-0.98, 3.72]; Std. beta = 0.69, 95% CI [-0.49, 1.86])
  • The effect of family income [40000_above] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.35, S.E. = 1.22, p = 0.775, 95% CI [-2.74, 2.04]; Std. beta = -0.18, 95% CI [-1.38, 1.02])
  • The effect of number volunteer r is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.81, S.E. = 0.41, p = 0.050, 95% CI [1.22e-03, 1.61]; Std. beta = 0.39, 95% CI [5.93e-04, 0.78])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 1.20, S.E. = 0.78, p = 0.122, 95% CI [-0.32, 2.73]; Std. beta = 0.60, 95% CI [-0.16, 1.37])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.

nb_mcs

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict nb_mcs with age, gender, marital, education, family_income, number_volunteer_r and time_point (formula: nb_mcs ~ 1 + age + gender + marital + education + family_income + number_volunteer_r + time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.77) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.28. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, gender = female, marital = divorced, education = secondary, family_income = 0_10000, number_volunteer_r = 0 and time_point = 1st , is at 49.84 (S.E. = 13.81, p < .001, 95% CI [22.78, 76.90]).
